05196nam a22009255i 9780520936294DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696585  a97805209362947 a10.1525/97805209362942doi  a(DE-B1597)519949  a(OCoLC)52842783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aF3430.1.M3 4aF3430.1.M3bJ64 2003 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.898/392211 aJohnson, Allen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFamilies of the Forest :bThe Matsigenka Indians of the Peruvian Amazon /cAllen Johnson. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (275 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Among the Matsigenka -- tChapter 1. Setting and History -- tChapter 2. Making a Living -- tChapter 3. Family Life -- tChapter 4. Society and Politics -- tChapter 5. Cosmos -- tConclusion: A Family Level Society -- tGlossary -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe idea of a family level society, discussed and disputed by anthropologists for nearly half a century, assumes moving, breathing form in Families of the Forest. According to Allen Johnson’s deft ethnography, the Matsigenka people of southeastern Peru cannot be understood or appreciated except as a family level society; the family level of sociocultural integration is for them a lived reality. Under ordinary circumstances, the largest social units are individual households or small extended-family hamlets. In the absence of such "tribal" features as villages, territorial defense and warfare, local or regional leaders, and public ceremonials, these people put a premium on economic self-reliance, control of aggression within intimate family settings, and freedom to believe and act in their own perceived self-interest.Johnson shows how the Matsigenka, whose home is the Amazon rainforest, are able to meet virtually all their material needs with the skills and labor available to the individual household. They try to raise their children to be independent and self-reliant, yet in control of their emotional, impulsive natures, so that they can get along in intimate, cooperative living groups. Their belief that self-centered impulsiveness is dangerous and self-control is fulfilling anchors their moral framework, which is expressed in abundant stories and myths. Although, as Johnson points out, such people are often described in negative terms as lacking in features of social and cultural complexity, he finds their small-community lifestyle efficient, rewarding, and very well adapted to their environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMachiguenga IndiansxKinship. 0aMachiguenga IndiansxSocial life and customs. 0aMachiguenga cosmology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aamazon rainforest.  aanthropologists.  aanthropology.  acultural anthropology.  acultural framework.  acultural social.  adiscussion books.  aeconomic self reliance.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  afamily level society.  afamily settings.  aforest life.  aharsh conditions.  ahousehold economy.  aindigenous peoples.  amatsigenka indians.  anative indians.  anonfiction.  aperu.  aperuvian amazon.  aself reliance.  asocial sciences.  asocial studies.  asocial units.  asociocultural perspective.  atextbooks.  atheoretical.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023242640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093629440